The start symbol has only one rule:

S → NT29 NT21

NT29 can eventually produce only the single terminal t48 (NT29 → 't48'), so the first symbol of any string in the language must be t48 – which matches the given string.

The remainder of the string must be generated by NT21.  
NT21 has only one rule:

NT21 → NT55 NT52

Thus the string produced by NT21 consists of:
• the string generated by NT55, followed by  
• exactly one terminal generated by NT52.

NT52, however, can generate only the single terminals t63 or t97:

NT52 → 't63' | 't97'

Hence any string in the language must end with either t63 or t97.  
The given string ends with t20, not t63 or t97.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The only production for the start symbol is  

S → NT29 NT21  

and the only production for NT29 is  

NT29 → 't48'  

Therefore any string generated by the grammar must begin with the terminal t48.  
The given string begins with t93, so it cannot be derived from S.
